The lineage of Jesus Christ.
The book of the birth of Jesus Christ, the Son of David, the Son of Abraham:
Ibrahim is the son of Isaac. Isaac is the son of Jacob. Jacob is the son of Judah and his brothers.
Judah had Peresh and Zerah, sons of Tamar. Peresh had Serah, and Serah had Aram.
And Aram was the father of Ehud, and Ehud was the father of Asael.
And Salmon begat Boaz from Rahab. And Boaz begat Obed from Ruth. And Obed begat Jesse.
And Solomon the king begat Rehoboam. And Rehoboam the king begat Abijam.
Solomon was born to Rehabeam. Rehabeam was the son of Abijah. Abijah was the father of Asa.
And Asa begat Jehoshaphat. Jehoshaphat begat Joram. Joram begat Azariah.
And Hezekiah was the son of Ahaz. And Ahaz was the son of Jotham. And Jotham was the son of Uzziah.
Hezekiah was the son of Manasseh. Manasseh was the son of Amon. Amon was the son of Josiah.
And Josiah was born to Jehoiakin and his brothers during the Babylonian captivity.
And after the captivity in Babylon, Yehoiakin was born to Jechaniah. Jechaniah begat Serubbabel.
Zarbabel was the father of Abiud. Abiud was the father of Eliacim. Eliacim was the father of Azariah.
And Azur was the son of Zadok. Zadok was the son of Ahim. Ahim was the son of Eliud.
And Eliud begat Eleazar. Eleazar begat Metan. Metan begat Jacob.
Jacob, the son of Joseph, was the husband of Mary, who gave birth to Jesus, who is called Christ.
All the generations from Abraham to David are fourteen; and from David to the carrying away into Babylon, fourteen; and from the carrying away into Babylon to Christ, fourteen. The birth of Jesus Christ.
Now the birth of Jesus Christ took place in this way. When his mother Mary was betrothed to Joseph, before they came together, she found herself with child from the Holy Spirit.
Yusuf was her husband since he was righteous, but he did not want to make her public, he wanted to divorce her secretly.
But while he was pondering these things, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream, saying, "Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to take Mary as your wife, for that which is conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit."
He laid his sons to rest and named him Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins.
And all this was to fulfill what the Lord said through the prophet:
Behold, a virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and his name shall be called Emmanuel, which means, God with us.
When Joseph awoke from sleep, he did as the angel of the Lord had commanded him, and took his wife.
He did not know her until she gave birth to her firstborn son. And he named him Jesus.
The visit of the Magi
When Jesus was born in Bethlehem in Judea during the reign of King Herod, magi from the east came to Jerusalem.
Saying, "Where is he who is born King of the Jews? For we have seen his star in the east and have come to worship him."
When King Herod heard this, he was disturbed, and all Jerusalem with him.
Then he gathered all the chief priests and the scribes of the people, and asked them, "Where is the Christ born?"
And they said unto him, In Bethlehem of Judah: for thus it is written by the prophet,
And thou, Bethlehem, land of Judah, art not the least among the rulers of Judah: for out of thee shall come a ruler that shall shepherd my people Israel."
Then Herod secretly called the magi and inquired from them the time of the star's appearance.
Then he sent them to Bethlehem, saying, "Go and search carefully for the child, and when you have found him, bring me word, that I too may come and bow down before him."
When they heard the king's words, they left. And the star which they had seen in the east went before them, until it came and stood over where the child was.
When they saw the star, they rejoiced with great joy.
And they came to the house, and saw the boy with Mary his mother. And they bowed down and worshiped him. Then they opened their treasures and presented him with gifts: gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
Then it was revealed to them in a dream that they should not return to Herod, but take a different road back to their own country. So they left and went to Egypt.
And when they had departed, behold, the angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream, saying, Arise, and take the child and his mother, and flee into Egypt, and be there until I tell thee; for Herod is about to seek the child to destroy him.
So he got up, took the boy and his mother by night, and departed to Egypt.
And he was there until the death of Herod. In order that what was spoken by the Lord through the prophet might be fulfilled: "I called my son out of Egypt."
Then Herod, seeing that the magi had derided him, was very angry; and he sent forth and killed all the children in Bethlehem and in all the region thereof, from two years old and under, according to the time which he had inquired of the magi.
Then it was fulfilled what was said by the prophet Jeremiah:
A voice was heard in Ramah, wailing and great mourning. Rachel wept for her children, and refused to be comforted, for they were no more. Return to Nazareth.
And when Herod was dead, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph in Egypt,
Saying, "Arise, take the child and his mother, and go into the land of Israel; for those who sought the boy are dead."
So he arose, took the boy and his mother, and came into the land of Israel.
But when he heard that Archelaus had the rule over Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there. And being warned in a dream, he withdrew into the region of Galilee.
And he came and dwelt in a city called Nazareth, that it might be fulfilled which was spoken by the prophets, That he should be called a Nazarite.
John the Baptist is preparing the way.
And in those days John the Baptist came, preaching in the wilderness of Judea.
Saying, "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand."
For this is what was said by the prophet Isaiah: "A voice crying out in the wilderness: Prepare the way of the Lord; make his paths straight."
And John was clothed with camel's hair, and had a leather belt around his waist. And his food was locusts and wild honey.
Then Jerusalem and all Judea, and all the region around the Jordan, went out to meet him.
They relied on him in Jordan, acknowledging their sins.
When he saw many of the Pharisees and Sadducees coming to his baptism, he said to them, "You offspring of vipers, how are you to escape the coming wrath?"
So make fruits befitting repentance.
And do not think that you can say in your hearts, 'We have Abraham as our father.' For I tell you that out of these stones God can raise up children to Abraham.
And now the ax is laid to the root of the tree; every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
I baptize you with water for repentance, but he who comes after me is mightier than I, of whom I am not worthy to untie the thong of his sandals. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and with fire.
He who holds the flail in his hand, and will thresh his wheat, and gather it into the barn, but the chaff he will burn with fire that is never quenched." (Baptism of Jesus Christ)
Then Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan to be baptized by John.
But John stopped him, saying, "I need to be baptized by you, and you come to me?"
Then Jesus answered and said unto him, "Let it be now, for so it befit us to fulfill all righteousness." And he allowed him.
When Jesus had been baptized, he came up out of the water; and lo, the heavens were opened to him, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and coming on him.
And a voice from the heavens said, "This is My beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased."
Jesus faces the temptation.
Then Jesus was led by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil.
After forty days and forty nights of fasting, he finally became hungry.
Then the demon approached him and said, "If you are the son of God, make these stones into bread."
Then he answered and said, "It is written, 'Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds out of the mouth of God.'"
Then Satan took him to the holy city, and stood him on the wing of the temple,
And he said to him, "If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down, for it is written: 'He will give his angels charge over you, to keep you, and to bear you up on their hands, lest you strike your foot against a stone.'"
Jesus said to him, "It is also written: Do not put the Lord your God to the test."
Then Satan took him to a very high mountain, and showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory.
And he said to him, "I will give you all these, if you prostrate yourself and worship me."
Then Jesus said to him, "Go, Satan! For it is written, 'You shall worship the Lord your God, and Him alone shall you serve.'"
Then Satan left him, and angels came and served him. The beginning of his service was in Galilee.
When Jesus heard that John had been imprisoned, he withdrew to Galilee.
And he left Nazareth, and came and dwelt in Capernaum, which is by the sea, in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali.
As it is written in the prophet Isaiah:
The land of Zebulun, and the land of Naphtali, By the sea, by the Jordan, Galilee of the Gentiles.
The people sitting in darkness have seen a great light, and those sitting in the valley of death and shadows have had light shine on them."
From that time Jesus began to preach and say, "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven has come near." The first call of the disciples.
And walking by the Sea of Galilee, he saw two brothers, Simon who is called Peter, and Andrew his brother, casting a net into the sea; for they were fishermen.
Then he said to them, "Come after me, and I will make you fishers of men."
For the moment they left the window and followed him.
Then he passed by there and saw two other brothers: James, son of Zebedee, and John his brother, in a ship with their father Zebedee mending their nets, and he called them.
At once they left the ship and their father, and followed him. Jesus taught and healed the sick.
And Jesus was traveling throughout Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, proclaiming the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every weakness among the people.
The news of his healing spread throughout Syria. They brought to him all the sick, those suffering from various diseases and ailments, the insane, the possessed, and the paralyzed, and he healed them all.
And a great multitude followed him from Galilee, and from the Decapolis, and from Jerusalem, and from Judea, and even from beyond the Jordan.
The Sermon on the Mount - The Beatitudes
And when the crowd saw him, they went up to the mountain; and when he had sat down, his disciples came to him.
Then he opened his mouth and taught them, saying:
Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are the sad, for they will be comforted.
Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.
Blessed are the hungry and thirsty for righteousness, for they will be satisfied.
Blessed are the merciful, for they shall be merciful.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called the children of God.
Blessed are the outcast for righteousness' sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are you when they insult you and persecute you and say all manner of evil against you on my account.
Rejoice and be glad, for great is your reward in heaven; for they persecuted the prophets who were before you, even as they persecuted you. Salt of the earth and light of the world.
You are the salt of the earth, but if salt has lost its taste, how can it be seasoned? It is no longer good for anything, but is fit only to be thrown out and trampled underfoot by men.
You are the light of the world. A city that is set on a hill cannot be hidden.
They do not light a lamp and put it under a bushel, but on a stand, and it gives light to all in the house.
Let your light so shine before men, that they may see your good works, and glorify your Father which is in heaven. Fulfilling the law.
Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets. I have not come to abolish but to fulfill.
Verily I say unto you, until heaven and earth pass, not an iota or a dot shall pass from the law until all is fulfilled.
For whoever breaks one of these least commandments and teaches others to do so will be called the least in the kingdom of heaven. But whoever does and teaches will be called great in the kingdom of heaven.
For I tell you, unless your righteousness exceeds that of the scribes and Pharisees, you will not enter the kingdom of heaven.
You have heard that it was said to the ancients, "Do not kill," and whoever kills will be subject to judgment.
But I say to you, whoever is angry with his brother without a cause is subject to judgment; and whoever says to his brother, 'Raca,' is liable to the Sanhedrin; and whoever says, 'You fool,' is subject to the fire of hell.
If you bring your gift to the altar, and there remember that your brother has something against you,
Leave your offering there, in front of the altar, and first go and reconcile with your brother. Then come and offer your offering.
Be a friend to your enemy quickly while you are with him, lest he deliver you to the judge, and the judge deliver you to the policeman, and you end up in prison.
I tell you truly, do not leave here until you have paid the last farthing! Adultery
You have heard it said to the ancients, "Do not commit adultery."
But I tell you, whoever looks at a woman with lust has already committed adultery with her in his heart.
"If your right eye causes you to sin, pluck it out and throw it away; it is better for you that one of your members should perish, and not your whole body be thrown into hell."
"If your right hand causes you to stumble, cut it off and throw it away; it is better for you that one of your members perish rather than your whole body be thrown into hell." (Divorce)
And it is said: Whoever divorces his wife should give her a divorce document.
And I say to you: Whoever divorces his wife, except for marital unfaithfulness, causes her to commit adultery; and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. (The verse is from the Quran, sura 5, ayat 32.)
You have also heard it said to the ancients, "Do not break your oath, but fulfill your vows to the Lord."
And I say to you, do not swear at all, not by heaven, for it is God's throne.
Not by the land, for it is his footstool, nor by Jerusalem, for it is the city of the great King.
Do not swear by your head, for you cannot make a single hair white or black.
But let your 'yes' be 'yes', and your 'no', 'no'. Whatever is beyond these is evil. Retaliation
You have heard it said: an eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth.
And I say to you, do not resist evil, but whoever strikes you on the right cheek, turn the other to him as well.
And if anyone wants to sue you and take your coat, leave him the cloak as well.
And whoever makes you go one mile, go with them two.
Give to him who asks, and do not refuse him who borrows. Love your enemies.
You have heard it said: love your neighbor and hate your enemy.
And I say to you, Love your enemies. Bless those who curse you. Do good to those who hate you, and pray for those who persecute you.
That you may be sons of your Father who is in heaven, the sun shines on the evil and on the good, and the rain falls on the righteous and on the unrighteous.
For if you love those who love you, what reward do you have? Do not even the tax collectors do the same?
And if you greet only your brothers, what good are you doing? Do not even the Gentiles do the same?
Be perfect, even as your Father in heaven is perfect.
Charity
Beware of performing your acts of charity before men to be seen by them, for otherwise you have no reward with your Father who is in heaven.
For when you give alms, do not sound a trumpet before you, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, to gain the praise of men. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward!
And as for you, when you give alms, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing.
So that your charity may be in secret. For your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Prayer
And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, who love to pray standing in synagogues and at the corners of streets, that they may be seen by men. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward.
But you, when you pray, go into your room and shut the door, and pray to your Father who is in secret. And your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly.
And when you pray, do not use vain repetitions as the Gentiles do, for they think that their many words will avail them.
Do not follow their example. For your Father knows what you need, even before you ask Him.
"Pray thus: Our Father who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name."
Your kingdom come. Your will be done on earth as it is in heaven.
Give us this day our daily bread.
And forgive us our sins as we forgive those who sin against us.
Do not put us to the test, but deliver us from evil. For yours is the kingdom, and the power, and the glory, forever. Amen.
For if you forgive men their transgressions, your Heavenly Father will also forgive you.
"If you do not forgive others their mistakes, your Father will not forgive your mistakes either." (The Fasting)
And when you fast, do not look gloomy, like the hypocrites, for they change their faces to show the people that they are fasting. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward.
And as for you, when you are silent, anoint your head and wash your face.
So that you may not appear to men to be fasting, but to your Father who is in secret. For your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Treasures in heaven.
Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and rust corrupt, and where thieves break in and steal.
But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust corrupts, and where thieves do not break in and steal;
For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.
The light of the body is the eye; if your eye is simple, then your whole body will be full of darkness.
And if your eye be evil, your whole body shall be full of darkness; if therefore the light that is in thee be darkness, how great is that darkness!
No one can serve two masters, for either he will hate the one and love the other, or he will be devoted to one and despise the other. You cannot serve God and money. God provides for us.
Therefore I say to you, Do not be anxious about your life, what you will eat or what you will drink; nor about your body, what you will wear. Is not life more than food, and the body more than clothes?
Look at the birds of the sky; they neither sow nor reap nor gather into barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not much more valuable than they?
And of you, who, if he were to care, could add even one span to his height?
And why do you care about clothing? Consider the lilies of the field, how they grow without toil or spinning.
But I say to you, not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of them.
For if the grass of the field, which today is and tomorrow is cast into the oven, God does so, how much more shall you clothe yourselves, you of little faith?
Do not therefore worry, saying, What shall we eat? or What shall we drink? or What shall we wear?
For these are what the nations seek. But your heavenly Father knows that you need all these things.
But seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and all these things will be added to you.
Do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about itself. Suffice for the day its own trouble.
Condemning others
Do not judge, so that you will not be judged.
For with the judgment you judge, you will be judged; and with the measure you use, it will be measured to you.
Why do you see the speck that is in your brotherâ€™s eye, and do not perceive the beam that is in your own eye?
Mother, or how do you say to your brother: Let me remove the speck from your eye, and look, there is a log in your eye?
You hypocrite, take the beam out of your own eye first, and then you will see clearly to take the speck out of your brother's eye!
Do not give Jerusalem to the dogs, and do not throw your pearls before swine, lest they trample them with their feet and turn and tear you to pieces. Ask, seek, knock.
Ask and ye shall receive. Seek and ye shall find. Knock and it shall be opened unto you.
For whoever asks receives, and whoever seeks finds, and to whoever knocks, the door will be opened.
Would any of you give your son a stone when he asks for bread?
And if asked for a fish, would he give a snake?
For if you, being evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father who is in heaven give good things to those who ask him!
Whatever you want people to do to you, do the same to them; for this is the Law and the Prophets. The Narrow Door
Enter through the narrow door, for the gate is wide and the way is easy that leads to destruction, and there are many who enter through it!
How narrow the door and how difficult the path that leads to life! And few find it. The tree and its fruit.
Beware of false prophets who come to you in sheep's clothing, but inwardly they are ravenous wolves!
You shall know them by their fruits. Do grapes grow on thorns, or figs on thistles?
Thus every good tree bears good fruit, but a bad tree bears bad fruit.
A good tree cannot bear bad fruit, nor can a bad tree bear good fruit.
Every tree that bears not good fruit is cut down and cast into the fire.
You will know them by their fruits.
Not everyone who says, 'Lord, Lord,' will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only he who does the will of my Father in heaven.
Many will say to me on that day, "Lord, Lord!" Will it not be because in your name we prophesied, and in your name we cast out demons, and in your name we did many wonders?
Then I will declare to them, "I never knew you! Depart from me, you workers of iniquity!" The wise builders and the ignorant builders.
"But whoever hears my words and acts on them, is like a wise man who built his house on a rock."
And the rain fell, and the rivers came, and the winds blew, and the house stood firm because it had been founded on a rock.
And whoever hears these words of mine and does not put them into practice is like a foolish man who built his house on sand.
And the rain fell, and the rivers came, and the winds blew, and the house was struck and fell with a great crash.
When Jesus had finished saying these things, the crowd was amazed at his teaching.
Because he taught them as one with authority, not like scribes.
Curing leprosy
And when he came down from the mountain, great crowds followed him.
And if a leper came and bowed down to him, saying, "Master, if you will, you can cleanse me."
Then Jesus stretched out his hand and touched him, saying, "I do will it, be thou cleansed." And immediately his leprosy was cleansed.
Then Jesus said to him, "See that you do not tell anyone. But go, show yourself to the priest, and offer the sacrifice that Moses commanded, as a testimony for them." The faith of the centurion.
When Jesus entered Capernaum, a centurion came to him, asking him to do something.
He says, "O Lord, my servant lies in the house, paralyzed and in great pain."
Then Jesus said to him, "I will come and heal him."
Then the captain of the hundred answered and said, "Lord, I am not worthy that thou shouldest come under my roof: but speak a word, and my servant shall be made whole."
Because I am also under authority. I have soldiers under my command. I say to this one, 'Go!' and he goes; to another, 'Come!' and he comes; to my servant, 'Do this!' and he does it.
When Jesus heard this, he marveled, and said to those who followed him, "I tell you the truth, I have not found such faith, not even in Israel!"
And I say to you, many will come from the east and the west, and will sit down with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven.
And those in the kingdom will be thrown into outer darkness. There will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
Then Jesus said to the centurion, 'Go, and as you have believed, so let it be done for you.' And his servant was healed in that hour. Healing of Peter's mother-in-law and others.
When Jesus came to Peter's house, he found his mother-in-law lying sick with a fever.
He touched her hand, and the fever left her, so she got up and served them.
And when evening had come, many possessed people were brought to him. And he cast out the devils with a word, and healed all the sick.
That which was spoken by the prophet Isaiah, who said: "He took our sicknesses and carried our diseases." The cost of dependence.
And when Jesus saw great multitudes about him, he commanded to go over to the other side.
Then a scribe came up and said to him, "Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go."
Then Jesus said to him, "The foxes have holes, and the birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head."
And one of his disciples said to him, "Lord, permit me to go first and bury my father."
Then Jesus said to him, "Follow me, and let the dead bury their dead." Calming the storm
And when he entered the ship, his disciples followed him.
And if a great storm arose in the sea, so that the waves covered the ship, he was sleeping.
Then his disciples came and awoke him, saying, "Master, save us; we are perishing!"
He said to them, "Why are you afraid, O you of little faith?" Then he rose and rebuked the winds and the sea, and there was a great calm.
And the people were amazed, saying, "Who is this man? For even the winds and the sea obey him!" And he cast out demons.
And when he came to the other side, to the region of the Gerasenes, two possessed men coming out of the tombs met him, extremely violent, so that no one could pass that way.
And when they cried out, saying, "What have we to do with you, Jesus, Son of God? Have you come here to torment us before time?"
And nearby, a great herd of pigs was feeding.
The demons begged him, saying, "If you cast us out, let us go to the herd of pigs."
And he said unto them, "Go." And they went out and went to the herd of pigs, and behold, all the herd of pigs had rushed down the cliff into the sea, and perished in the waters.
But the shepherds fled and went into the city, and told everything and the story of the madmen.
For all the city came out to meet Jesus. And when they saw him, they asked him to leave their borders.
Curing paralysis
He entered the ship, passed through, and came to his city.
And if a paralytic is brought to him lying on a bed, when Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic, "Take heart, son; your sins are forgiven."
And if a group of the scribes say to themselves, "This is blasphemy!"
Jesus, knowing their thoughts, said, "Why do you have evil thoughts in your hearts?"
Which is easier: to say, "Your sins are forgiven," or to say, "Get up and walk"?
But that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then he said to the paralytic, "Get up, take your mat and go home!"
He got up and went home.
When they saw the crowd, they were amazed and glorified God, who had given people such authority. A call from Matthew.
And as Jesus was passing by, he saw a man sitting by the tax collector's booth, named Matthew. And he said to him, "Follow me." And he rose up and followed him.
And while he was sitting at home, many tax collectors and sinners came and sat down with Jesus and his disciples.
When the Pharisees saw this, they said to his disciples, "Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?"
When Jesus heard it, he said to them, "The well do not need a physician, but the sick."
Go and learn what this means: I desire mercy, not sacrifice; for I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance." (On fasting)
Then the disciples of John came to him and said, "Why do we and the Pharisees fast often, but your disciples do not fast?"
Then Jesus said to them, "Can the bridegrooms mourn while the bride is with them? But the days will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them; then they will fast."
No one sews a patch of new cloth on an old garment, for the new takes away from the old, and the patch would turn the rest bad.
Do not put new wine into old wineskins, lest the wineskins burst, and the wine be spilled, and the wineskins be destroyed. But put new wine into new wineskins, and both will be preserved." (Luke 5:37-39) "And a woman suffering from bleeding stopped flowing when she touched the cloth that Jesus had touched." (Luke 8:44)
And while he was speaking these things, behold, a ruler came and knelt before him, saying, "My daughter is now dead; but come and lay your hand on her, and she will live."
Jesus got up and followed him, along with his disciples.
And if a woman with a flow of blood for twelve years came from behind him and touched the hem of his garment,
Because she said to herself, "If I but touch his garment, I will be healed."
Jesus turned and saw her, and said, "Daughter, your faith has made you well." And from that hour the woman was healed.
When Jesus came to the ruler's house, he saw the musicians and the crowd making a noise.
He said to them, "Step aside, for the child is not dead but sleeping." And they laughed at him.
When he went out, the crowd came in and grabbed her hand, so the girl stood up.
And the news spread throughout the whole land. Healing of the blind.
And as Jesus passed by, two blind men followed him, crying out and saying, "Have mercy on us, O Son of David!"
And when he came to the house, the blind came to him, and Jesus said to them, "Do you believe that I am able to do this?" They said to him, "Yes, Lord!"
Then he touched their eyes, saying, "According to your faith, be it unto you."
And their eyes were opened. And Jesus rebuked them, saying, "See, it is no one's business!"
But they went out and preached it in that whole region, and healed the mute.
And as they were going out, a mute, madman was brought to him.
And when the devil had spoken, the mute spake; and the multitude marveled, saying, Never was such a thing heard in Israel!
But the Pharisees said, "By the prince of devils he casts out devils!" The works are few.
And Jesus was traveling through all the towns and villages, teaching in their synagogues, and preaching the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every weakness among the people.
And when he saw the crowd, he had compassion on them, for they were like sheep without a shepherd.
At that time, he said to his disciples, "The harvest is plentiful, but the workers are few."
So they asked the Lord of the harvest to send laborers to his harvest.
Sending the Twelve
Then he called his twelve disciples and gave them authority over unclean spirits to cast them out, and to heal every disease and every weakness.
